Abstract¶

In a bike-sharing system, the prediction of the availability of the bikes is crucial for providing efficient service. In this report, we will simulate the number of available bikes every 10-minutes of the morning and evening hours using Makov Chains. By doing that, we are estimating the steady-state of the number of available bikes in a station.

We use CitiBike data collected from NYC to build a Markov Chain model for each bike station.

The analysis and results presented in the report can provide insights on how to better manage the bike-sharing system in popular areas around NYC to provide an optimal customer-centric service.

As shown above, this dataset contains Citibike rides in NYC that happened in July 2022. The dataset contains 3,497,390 rows and 13 columns. Each row corresponds to a ride (i.e., a trip). The columns give the ride ID, the ride type (classic, electric), the start time of the ride, the end time of the ride, the start station name and ID, the end station name and ID and other information.

Please find a detailed description of the dataset at the following link https://ride.citibikenyc.com/system-data.

Note that the data has already been cleaned by CitiBike.

Pre-processing the dataset¶

To answet the warm-up questions, we first created a column to the dataframe that calculates the duration of each trip.
We do that using the datetime library and by subtracting “started_at” from “ended_at”. This column is converted to seconds and then we removed the rows that had negative values or values greater than 10,800 = 3 hours, since these are likely bikes that were left undocked.

Question 2: What is the expected ride duration (i.e., the average ride duration)? What is the empirical variance of ride duration? What is the probability that a ride duration is greater than 20 min?¶

The expected ride duration can be calculated as

$\frac{Sum\:of\:duration\:of\:every\:ride}{number\:of\:all\:ride}$

The empirical variance of ride duration can be calculated as below

$\sigma^2 = \frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}(d_i - \mu)^2} {n-1}$
While $d_i$ is the duration of every ride and $\mu$ is average ride duration

Lastly, the probability that a ride duration is greater than 20 min can be calculated as:

$\frac{number\:of\:rides\:with\:duration\:>20\:minute}{number\:of\:all\:ride}$

The result can be viewed as below

In [36]:
print("The expected ride duration is", round(df_less_than_3_hours['duration_in_minutes'].mean(), 2),"minutes")
print("The empirical variance of ride duration is", round(df_less_than_3_hours['duration_in_minutes'].var(), 2))
dur_greater_20_min = len(df_less_than_3_hours[df_less_than_3_hours['duration_in_minutes'] > 20])/len(df_less_than_3_hours)
print("The probability that a ride duration is greater than 20 min is", round(dur_greater_20_min, 2))

The expected ride duration is 14.99 minutes
The empirical variance of ride duration is 232.81
The probability that a ride duration is greater than 20 min is 0.23

Question 4: Suppose that the duration of some ride is more than 25min. What is the probability that this ride belongs to a CitiBike member?¶

The probability that we want to calculate is: P(rider=CitiBike member | duration>25 mins) and with Bayes Rule we have: $$=\frac{P(duration>25 mins | rider=CitiBike \: member) P(rider=CitiBike \: member)}{P(duration>25 mins | rider=CitiBike \: member) P(rider=CitiBike \: member) + P(duration>25 mins | rider=Casual) P(rider=Casual)}$$

Below we calculate each probability

Question 6: Suppose that the duration of some ride is less than 10min. What is the probability that this ride uses an electric bike? What is the probability that this ride uses a classic bike? Comment on the results.¶

We used the two equations below (Baye's Rule) to calculate the probabilities. We then checked our computation by calculating the probabilities using a compact code format.

P(rideable type=electric bike | duration<10 mins) and with Bayes Rule we have: $$=\frac{P(duration<10 mins | electric \: bike \:) P(electric\: bike \:)}{P(duration<10 mins | electric \: bike \: ) P(electric \: bike \:) + P(duration<10 mins | classic) P(classic)\:) +P(duration<10 mins | docked) P(docked)}$$

P(rideable type=classic bike | duration<10 mins) and with Bayes Rule we have: $$=\frac{P(duration<10 mins | classic \: bike \:) P(classic\: bike \:)}{P(duration<10 mins | classic \: bike \: ) P(classic \: bike \:) + P(duration<10 mins | electric) P(electric)\:) +P(duration<10 mins | docked) P(docked)}$$

Calculate the probailities as shown below:

/df_less_than_3_hours.shape[0]

/df_less_than_3_hours.shape[0]

/df_less_than_3_hours[df_less_than_3_hours['rideable_type']== "docked_bike"].shape[0]

prob_classic_given_duration = round((prob_duration_given_classic*prob_classic)\
/(prob_duration_given_classic*prob_classic+prob_duration_given_electric*prob_electric+\

prob_electric_given_duration = round((prob_duration_given_electric*prob_electric)\
/(prob_duration_given_classic*prob_classic+prob_duration_given_electric*prob_electric+\

P(electric bike| duration<10min) = 0.234
P(classic bike| duration<10min) = 0.763

Comment on the results:¶

The probability of a ride belonging to a classic bike given that it's <10 minutes is higher than the probability of a ride belonging to an electric bike given that it's <10 minutes (about 3 times higher). This tells us that most customers choose to ride a classic bike instead of an electric bike, when they are riding for a short period of time. This can be due to the fact that using an electric bike is more costly than using a classic bike. The other reason can be due to the fact that there are more available classic bikes than electric bikes.

Split the morning and the evening¶

We will define the two slots. We say that the morning slot is 7 am - 11 am and the evening slot is 4 pm - 8 pm.

This strategy was used to define the morning and evening slots because:

  • The morning hours and the evening hours could follow a certain pattern each.
  • 7am-11am is usually the time that people go to work/start their day. We did not want the data from previous hours to affect the study presented in this report. Similarily, the evening slot from 4pm-8pm is usually when people are commuting back home/leaving work.
  • We considered this as part of cleaning the data, similar to how the weekends and holidays were removed from the data.

Note that for the morning and evening slots, we kept the trips that started before the slot and ended in each slot and respectively started in the slot and ended after the slot. We will use these trips for the availability in the slot - in and out respectively.

Section 3: Time Discretization¶

To decide how long a state should be, we have a criteria as below:

  1. The state should long enough that we can observe a consider amount of activity in one state.
  2. The state should not last too long that there are significant difference among each state.

Keeping the criteria in mind, we will try to see the activity level of 10-minute state and 15-minute state and decide which is better for our used case.

Step 1: For simplicity, write a function that get the dataframe, duration of the state and output a table that's similar to the structure below¶

In [70]:
def create_markov_table(station_name, mins, df, morning):
    #if it's morning then input 1
    #Mins is the number of minutes in each state   
    period = mins
    n_state_day = 240/period
    df_station = df[(df['end_station_name']== station_name)|(df['start_station_name']==station_name)]
    date_drop_holiday_weekend = [1,5,6,7,8,11,12,13,14,15,18,19,20,21,22,25,26,27,28,29]
    markov_time = []
    out_list = []
    in_list = []
    if morning == 1:
        time_start = 7
    else:
        time_start = 16
    for d in date_drop_holiday_weekend:
        beginning_day_time = datetime(2022, 7, d, time_start, 0, 0, 0)
        for i in range(int(n_state_day)):
            num_in = 0
            num_out = 0
            time_in_state = beginning_day_time.timestamp()+i*period*60
            markov_time.append(datetime.fromtimestamp(time_in_state).strftime("%m/%d %H:%M:%S"))
            for index, row in df_station.iterrows():
                
                if ((beginning_day_time.timestamp()+i*period*60 < row['ended_at'].timestamp()+60*4*60) &
                    (beginning_day_time.timestamp()+(i+1)*period*60 > row['ended_at'].timestamp()+60*4*60)):
                    num_in +=1
                
                elif ((beginning_day_time.timestamp()+i*period*60 < row['started_at'].timestamp()+60*4*60) &
                      (beginning_day_time.timestamp()+(i+1)*period*60 > row['started_at'].timestamp()+60*4*60)):
                      num_out +=1
            out_list.append(num_out)
            in_list.append(num_in) 
    if morning ==1:
        print("The dataframe for",station_name,"_morning was constructed")
    else:
        print("The dataframe for",station_name,"_evening was constructed")    
    return pd.DataFrame({'time': markov_time,'In':in_list,'out':out_list})

Section 4: Estimation of Availability of Bikes in the Begining of July 1st and Every Day After¶

The initial state of the MC will be computed by following the method described below, for each time slot of each station. More specifically, we implemented this method for the estimation of available bikes in the beginning of each time slot (morning-evening) for each day and for every station. For this, we used the dataframe that is explained above for each time slot (morning-evening) and for every station (so in total we did it 6 times) and the capacity of each station. The capacity for the selected stations was estimated using the CitiBike application. Finding the stations at the application, we are able to see the classic and ebikes and the open docks. The summation of these provides the capacity of each station:

The capacity of West St. & Chambers St. Station is 79 bikes

The capacity of Westi 21 & 6th Avenue id 72 bikes

The capacity of Broadway and East 21 is 60 bikes

Having the above, we are using the dataframes of each time-slot (morning-evening) and the capacity of each station as inputs in a function (named get_df_with_availabilities) to create a column in the dataframes that has the availability at each 10-minutes slot. In this function, we are calculating the average “In” minus “Out”, and subtracting that from half the capacity. We round this number and assume that it is the available bikes right before this time-slot (i.e., morning or evening). This is because, statistically, if we didn't have any information, we would use just half of the capacity, but since we have ins and outs, we will use them to have an equilibrium for half of the capacity. Afterwards, we check if the availability at some 10-minutes slot exceeds the capacity or if the availability has a negative value, since the availability before the time-slot was a high-level estimation. We deal with the first occasion by subtracting the difference between the capacity and the maximum availability from the initial availability. Respectively, we deal with the second occasion by adding the absolute value of the most negative value of availability that occurs in that morning/evening time-slot. We do this procedure for all of the days - we compute the available bikes from the start for all days.

There were some occasions where the available bikes happened to have a negative value. We are assuming that this occurs, because some bikes are being manually moved to some stations and the data in these specific occasions (time slots) and these stations do not satisfy the constraints that at all stages the available bikes must be non-negative and less than the capacity. We are sure that they will not have a number greater than the capacity, since the constraint in the function described above first deals with the occasion that availability is greater than the capacity. In order to deal with this, we created a function (named change_range), that takes the morning/evening time-slots that this occurs and sets the range of availability to be equal to the capacity while maintaining the distribution (e.g., maintaining the fraction moving from one state to the next).

Finally, we check the maximum and minimum availability in each dataframe to make sure that they are non-negative and less than the capacity.

def get_availabilities_i_plus1_to_end_slot(df, i):
    for j in range(i+1, i+24):
        df.iloc[j, 3] = df.iloc[j-1, 3] + df.iloc[j, 1] - df.iloc[j, 2]
    return (df)
In [16]:
def get_df_with_availabilities(df, capacity):
    df['availability'] = np.nan
    i=0
    df.reset_index(drop=True, inplace=True)
    while i < 480:
        half = capacity/2
        temp = df.copy()
        temp = temp[i:i+24]
        temp['in_minus_out'] = temp.In - temp.out
        mean_in_minus_out = temp['in_minus_out'].mean()
        availabity_before_slot = half - mean_in_minus_out
        df.iloc[i, 3] = round(availabity_before_slot) + df.iloc[i, 1] - df.iloc[i, 2]
        df = get_availabilities_i_plus1_to_end_slot(df, i)
        if df[i: i+24]['availability'].max() > capacity:
            df.iloc[i, 3] = df.iloc[i, 3] - df[i: i+24]['availability'].max() + capacity
            df = get_availabilities_i_plus1_to_end_slot(df, i)
        elif df[i: i+24]['availability'].min() < 0:
            df.iloc[i, 3] = df.iloc[i, 3] + abs(df[i: i+24]['availability'].min())
            df = get_availabilities_i_plus1_to_end_slot(df, i)
        
        i += 24
    return (df)
In [17]:
def change_range(df, lista, capacity):
    for j in lista:
        old_range = df[j:j+24].availability.max() - df[j:j+24].availability.min()
        new_range = capacity
        old_min = df[j:j+24].availability.min()
        new_min = 0
        for i in df[j:j+24].index:
            df.iloc[i,3] = round((((df.iloc[i,3] - old_min) * new_range) / old_range) + new_min)
    return (df)

Deriving the Transition Matrix¶

We start by creating a (C+1) x (C+1) matrix for each station, given that C is the capacity of the station. +1 was used to add one row and one column, that correspond to the state where there are zero available bikes.
Then, we calculate $p_{ij}$ for $0\le i \le C$ and $0\le j \le C$ as the element ij of the matrix from the equation below:

$p_{ij} = \frac{f_{ij}}{\Sigma_j f_{ij}} $

where $f_{ij}$ is the number of times that the state changes from i to j, considering the whole month.
Below is the function that takes capacity as the input and outputs the transition matrix:

In [129]:
def get_transition_prob(df, capacity): 
    df['availability'] = df['availability'].astype(int)
    count_matrix = [[0 for i in range(capacity+1)] for j in range(capacity+1)]
    for i in np.arange(1,df.shape[0],1):
        count_matrix[df.at[i-1,'availability']][df.at[i,'availability']]+=1
    df_count = pd.DataFrame(count_matrix, columns = [i for i in np.arange(0,capacity+1,1)])
    #df_count.index = np.arange(1, len(df_count) + 1)
    df_count["sum"] = df_count.sum(axis=1)
    for i in np.arange(0,df_count.shape[0],1):
        if df_count.at[i,'sum'] == 0:
            df_count.at[i,'sum'] = 1
    df_count = df_count.loc[:,:].div(df_count["sum"], axis=0)
    df_count.drop(['sum'], axis=1, inplace = True)
    return df_count

Calculating the Stationary Distribution¶

Notice that the transition probability matrices are row stochastic since the sum of each row is 1. To calculate the morning and evening stationary distributions of each one of the 3 stations, we utilized the following equation: $πT=πTP$.

We defined a function that transposes a transition probability matrix to calculate eigenvectors of the stochastic rows. We then found the indexes of the eigenvalues that are close to one and used them to select the target eigen vectors. We then turned the eigenvector elements into probabilites. Finally, we defined the 6 stationary distributions and plotted the results.

In [134]:
from scipy.linalg import eig 
import seaborn as sns
In [135]:
def get_stationary_distribution(transition_matrix):
    eigenvals, eigenvects = np.linalg.eig(transition_matrix.T)
    
    close_to_1_idx = np.isclose(eigenvals,1)
    target_eigenvect = eigenvects[:,close_to_1_idx]
    target_eigenvect = target_eigenvect[:,0]
    
    stationary_distrib = target_eigenvect / sum(target_eigenvect) 
    return stationary_distrib

Results and Conclusion¶

Station 1: West St & Chambers St¶

After calculating and defining the morning and evening stationary distributions for station 1, we plotted the availability of bikes at the different states throughout the 10-minute discritized time increment against the probability, as shown below.

From the Morning plot, we can conclude that there will always be an available bike at the station. This is because the probability in the long run is zero to have less than 29 available bikes. So, there will be more than 29 available bikes and up to 74, with the highest probability of having 37 to 50 available bikes at the station (having 37 available bikes, has the highest long run probability, which is almost 5%). As calculated below, the probability of having 37 to 50 bikes is ~50%.

From the Evening plot, it appears that the probabilities are more evenly spread, which means that there will be different quantities of available bikes throughout the evening compared to the morning. This implies that there might be increased activity levels of bike usage. 38 and 40 available bikes seem to have the largest probabilities, which is around 4.5%. We can conclude that the available bikes reach the capacity of the station, with a probability of around 2%. This also means that there is a probability that there will be limited space for bikes coming into the station. Having more bike docks at this station can be beneficial.

Based on the above observations and the plots below, it appears that this CitiBike station usually has 25-60 bikes, which is good and means that people can find space to leave bikes they are returning or can find bikes to take out.

Station 2: W 21 St & 6 Ave¶

From the Morning plot of Station 2, we can see that having 72 bikes has the largest probability of around 4%, which means that there is a possibility that the number of bikes in the station reaches the capacity. Also, there is always available bikes at the station. The probability of having 20 to 50 bikes at the station is more than 50%, as calculated below.

From the Evening plot of Station 2, we notice that the probability of having zero bikes at the station is high (~3.5%). Moreover, the probability of having 72 bikes at the station is the largest (more than ~4%). This implies that this station might have capacity issues since its most likely to either have no available bikes or to have 72 bikes available. The probability of having different number of bikes is evenly spread.

Based on the above observations and the plots below, it appears that the number of available bikes at this CitiBike station with the largest probability is 72, which is the maximum capacity. This suggests that it would be beneficial to add more docks.

Station 3: Broadway & E 21 St¶

From the Morning plot of Station 3, we observe that there is a ~25% chance that the number of availbale bikes will be between 28 and 35 and ~40% chance that the number of available bikes will be between 49 and 60, as shown below. The largest number of availabel bikes with the highest probability of ~5% is 57.

From the Evening plot of Station 3, we notice that there is a possibility that there will be zero bikes at the station (around 2.5%). Moreover, the probability of having 60 bikes at the station is the largest (~5%). This implies that this station might have capacity issues since its most likely to either have no available bikes or to have 60 bikes available. The probability of having different number of bikes is evenly spread.

Based on the above observations and the plots below, it appears that it might be worth considering moving some bikes in the morning from this CitiBike station to a different station to better utilize the bikes and meet demand.

Report Notes¶

After running the analysis and studying the results, it is worth mentioning that the team expected to see graphs with positive and negative exponential stationary distributions; if the morning stationary distribution was positive, the evening would have been negative, and vice versa.

The reason behind the deviation of results from the expectations of the team was potentially due to the following reasons:

  1. The method used to estimate the number of available bikes at the initial state of the Markov Chain.
  2. The defined morning and evening timeframes.
